latestPosts.caption:
Tashi Namgyal, a Ladakhi shepherd from the village of Gharkon near Batalik in the Kargil sector, was the first to report Pakistan's infiltration to the Indian Army in May 1999. While searching for his missing yak around May 2-3, 1999, he spotted Pakistani soldiers in Pathan attire digging bunkers in the Batalik mountain range. Recognizing that these intruders had crossed the Line of Control, he promptly informed the nearest Indian Army post. His timely warning alerted the Indian Army, allowing them to verify the infiltration and prepare for the ensuing conflict known as the Kargil War. This intelligence was pivotal in shaping India's military response and ultimately securing victory in the war that lasted from May to July 1999.

Tashi Namgyal's role was widely recognized and he was repeatedly honored for his critical contribution. He passed away in late 2024, with the Indian Army paying tribute to his brave and selfless act that saved many lives and helped defend Indian territory.

Bollywood actor Avinash Tiwary took to social media and called out a Pakistani writer and celebrity stylist Rao Ali Khan for body-shaming him on social media. 

Boy! One has to give it to Avinash for replying to the aforementioned with utmost class!

For the unversed, while referring to Avinash’s physique in two of his recent shows, Khan had commented as, ‘Loved Bombay Meri Jaan. Was thinking why do you have belly fat in Khakhee and Bombay Meri Jaan both. Happy to see fitter body – super super. Loved Bombay Meri Jaan but pls loose [sic] weight and look fit.’

On his part, Avinash replied stating, ‘Sir, you are a journalist… if you had done any research you would know it was for the part... I suggest get beyond the idea of just vanity for cinema. Thank you’.

latestPosts.caption:
A major accident involving 15 to 20 vehicles, mostly cars, occurred today on the Mumbai-Pune Expressway near the Khopoli area. The accident happened between the New Tunnel and Foodmall Hotel when a container truck's brakes failed while descending the Lonavala-Khandala Ghat in the Mumbai-bound lane. The out-of-control container rammed into multiple vehicles, causing a large collision with several cars damaged.

There was 1 reported fatality and around 25 people injured in this crash. Despite the severity, no reports of multiple deaths have emerged so far. The accident caused a significant traffic jam on this busy weekend route. Emergency services and police quickly responded to the scene to manage rescue operations and traffic.

Image- abpnews (marathi)
